reviews.review_text:
Nak 700s done right... Well, it's sounds exactly like it should .. FOB which means "Front of Board" .  This is usually a "sweet spot" where the onstage volume blends with the PA in a triangular area or "spot" simple Left and Right ... The Nakamichi 700 has a open sound with brilliant mid range, highs and significant bass response.  However, what is really nice is the PA sounds good to me; it's loud and clear.  For me the real treat is to hear good cymbal definition which is tough to get right with two rock drummers!  I think the PA is mono as opposed to the GD can run stereo PA; supposedly Bear producer stereo PA by 1971. Of course, the wall of sound was quadrophonic at times.  The problem I have with stereo PA is the phase has to be correct , also using center fill is also a must aka LCR.  You see if you are too close to the stage many times you do not get the vocals.  However, the Grateful Dead is a exception , many tapes can demonstrate this is not the case.  I've had one time to be front row and yes , I could all the vocals (deer creek 91) .  There is a soundboard of this show which is pretty good but this audience is a treat in my opinion. 

The first set is well played overall lots of new and old stuff going on.  Jack Straw opener is hot and rock , not rock and roll , practically stadium rock . A rare electric version of On the Road Again, a rare early mid slot Touch of Grey (no new crap!) , ok; how bout the classic Dire Wolf , a uptempo Lazy Lightening , and a rocking Deal ! 

Second Set , they start to find the groove with a nice bubbly Shakedown St. , kicking' Samson, Terrapin Station is fairly stunning the crowd is actually quiet or mesmerized , the later !  Back with the new Throwing Stones and then come back to rock and roll GD with Not Fade Away ! Morning Dew slips out of surprise with the crowd appreciation ... wow, cap it off with a double encore ... great show and great upfront sound , yes.. you can hear the ride cymbal bell clearly ... enjoy ... worth a download for lovers
